Let‚Äôs take a moment to give a shout-out to Hoboken. As climate change delivers more extreme weather and rising seas, communities across the U.S. are struggling to prepare. That‚Äôs not Hoboken‚Äôs situation. New York City has been spending billions on flood walls and breakwaters and is still contemplating giant gates to hold back rising tides, but it hasn‚Äôt done as much to deal with rain. Hoboken has been adding infrastructure to cope with both rain and sea-level rise.

Hoboken‚Äôs goal is to collect and slow storm water. The city‚Äôs strategy has been to rebuild its sewers, adding capacity. The plan also bundles new infrastructure initiatives, which some see as invasive and time-consuming, with benefits residents desire, like new parks and playgrounds that have cisterns and basins. Streets redesigned to minimize traffic accidents also collect and redirect water: The redesign was a big reason the city bounced back so swiftly that rainy Friday in September, which dumped more than 3.5 inches of rain.

